⭐️Parent Survey⭐️

Dear GNTA Families & Guardians,

Thank you for your continued efforts as we finish the 2019-20 school year with distance learning. Many families want to know what is going to happen next school year. Right now, we don’t know what COVID-19-related health orders and social distancing will be like in August. That’s why we are creating a plan that includes several scenarios.

What is your family’s situation? Please take a few minutes to complete this family survey by June 12th. Your input will help as we continue to follow Sonoma County and California guidance to plan for a safe start to next school year.

We will be in touch with more information as soon as possible. Thank you once again for completing the family survey!

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/GMVPPBG

post_text:
Ms. Makino’s Art classes and their latest assignment:

Perhaps you have seen the image of “Amabie” presented as a symbol of hope during the pandemic.

According to legend, a mermaid-like creature emerged off the coast of Japan in 1846. She had long hair, a mouth like a bird's beak, three legs, and covered in scales from the neck down. She identified herself as Amabie and delivered a prophecy: “Good harvest will continue for six years from the current year. If an epidemic occurs, draw a picture of me and show it to everyone and they will be cured.” Then she returned to the sea.

GNTA art students were assigned to draw an original Amabie. The high school art students took this assignment one step further and mailed their drawing to a helpful person they care about in the GNTA community.

post_text:
💚 💛 A message from MR. BEKKER, to his Culinary Academy students (You can find this and other messages on ECHO):

Hey guys, during the next few weeks do everything in your powers to lessen the stress on your family by prepping and cooking for family meals. Now, more than ever, food and how that food plays a part in our relationships, plays a massive part of our lives.

A couple of tips:
Don't waste leftovers. Get creative on repurposing. Be inventive; think Chopped. We are going to get a little stir crazy without changes in our daily routine, so try to reinvent some meals. Take over the shopping list duties. It’s a great time to learn how much and what types a food your family normally uses. A tight list will also keep you from going to the store more often. Limit exposure. Stay safe and we'll see you soon.

Mr. Bekker
shared_text:
IVALUEFOOD.COM
Don’t Throw That Away! 10 Creative Ways to Use Leftovers

post_text: Ms. Kai and her students were INSPIRED by Recology Sonoma Marin’s presentation here at GNTA. After learning about recycling, waste reduction, and composting, they realized there wasn’t an easy way to dispose of plastic utensils 🍴. Often loose items cause problems in the recycling process. We now have collection bins so that they get thrown away together! This is just a temporary solution, of course, as they have more plans of how to reduce this entire need in the future.

post_text:
Read Across America is done.
We read books & had lots of fun.
Monday we read to our stuffed animals & decorated our door.
Tuesday we wore our hats & read some more.
Wednesday we wore mismatched socks & listened to special guests read to us.
Thursday we read in our pajamas & made no fuss.
Friday we wore green & we can all agree,
that we will continue to practice our reading & love books, you’ll see!

post_text: In Greek mythology, at the end of the phoenix’s life, it sets itself on fire and is then reborn from the ashes. Since the Kincade fire, Ms. Makino’s HS Art class used their vision of renewal, resilience, and beauty to create a “Phoenix Rising” mural. They used gold leaf, compressed charcoal, and charcoal from the burnt logs that were found on campus in the aftermath of the fire.

post_text: We are eternally grateful for our Geyserville Fire Department, Cal Fire, and ALL of the departments that saved our school and town. We are thankful for ALL of the organizations and neighbors that rallied around us, feeding our community, taking care of our animals, and comforting our children. We know some of our families lost their homes and how close we came to losing our school. This week, when we return, there will be lots of hugs and checking in with each other. We will move forward. Together.

post_text:
Geyserville Schools KID’S CAMP is happening this week while Geyserville Schools remain CLOSED. Parents that need to return to work or just need a breather, this is a great opportunity hosted by the B&G Club! Camp starts Monday, 11/4-Friday, 11/8 from 7:30am-4:30pm sharp at GES and is open to all TK-8th graders. *IMPORTANT* Please note some details and conditions below. More information will be provided as it becomes known to us.
*NO early drop offs or late pick ups allowed. Every child must be checked in each day. No exceptions. Please plan accordingly.
*Non-members of B&G Club and ALL 7th and 8th graders MUST fill out an application on site before entry.
*Breakfast and lunch will be served. Please send your child with a water bottle, sunscreen, and appropriate clothing.
*Up to 10 responsible, reliable high school students that are volunteering are allowed. They will be invited to leave if determined that they are not a good fit for the responsibility.

post_text: HAVE PLAYERS, NEED COACHES! Please help GNTA be able to have basketball teams this year. Call our Athletic Director, Sandy Frey, at the main office at 857-3592. Go Bronchos!

post_text: TODAY: Soccer at 4pm and Farmers Market from 3pm-6pm. Go Bronchos!
text: TODAY: Soccer at 4pm and Farmers Market from 3pm-6pm. Go Bronchos!

post_text: Tomorrow, come support our HS soccer team and their home game against Upper Lake at 4pm. While you’re here, the Farmers’ Market is happening from 3pm-6pm. They will have snacks and beverages in addition to veggies, herbs, and fruits. Go Bronchos!

post_text: Did you know? Our school district has many ways built in to support students. MS Homework Club, HS and MS Support electives, and B&G Club for K-6th, for example. There is also free tutoring at the Cloverdale library on Wednesdays. Call GNTA at 857-3592 or GES at 857-3410 for more details.

post_text: Next Wednesday, save the date: GES needs 4-5 parent volunteers to meet us at the Park & Ride and assist students in getting to school safely while they’re walking and rolling. Leave time is 7:45 am.
